01:18:34,971 --> 01:18:38,801
But I do know someone who could
get his fax number for you.

1287
01:18:39,889 --> 01:18:41,194
Shall we dance?

1288
01:18:41,238 --> 01:18:42,935
[BAND PLAYING]

1289
01:18:49,681 --> 01:18:51,204
[PEOPLE WHOOPING]

1290
01:19:04,000 --> 01:19:05,784
[EXCLAIMING]

1291
01:19:10,876 --> 01:19:13,052
[EXCLAIMING]

1292
01:19:26,936 --> 01:19:29,808
Well, any rings on fingers?

1293
01:19:29,852 --> 01:19:32,202
Oh, Gareth, you don't know
how lucky you are.

1294
01:19:32,245 --> 01:19:34,682
Finding someone to marry
is a very tricky business.

1295
01:19:34,726 --> 01:19:36,554
It's hell out there.

1296
01:19:36,597 --> 01:19:39,296
Matthew's trapped with an
evangelist from Minnesota.

1297
01:19:42,821 --> 01:19:45,868
My lords, ladies, and gentlemen,

1298
01:19:45,911 --> 01:19:48,044
please charge your glasses.

1299
01:19:48,087 --> 01:19:51,482
First, and rather unusually,
we have the bride.

1300
01:19:51,525 --> 01:19:53,963
[PEOPLE APPLAUDING]

1301
01:19:54,006 --> 01:19:56,052
Excellent.
I love this girl.

1302
01:19:57,270 --> 01:19:59,403
CARRIE: Thank you.

1303
01:19:59,446 --> 01:20:00,989
First of all, I'd like
to thank all of you

1304
01:20:01,013 --> 01:20:02,580
who've flown in from the States.

1305
01:20:02,623 --> 01:20:05,061
I'm really touched.

1306
01:20:05,104 --> 01:20:07,890
And, as for the rest of you,
I would have thought

1307
01:20:07,933 --> 01:20:09,998
the fact that lots of frightful
Americans were flying in

1308
01:20:10,022 --> 01:20:12,633
was the perfect excuse for
staying away, so I thank you, too.

1309
01:20:12,677 --> 01:20:13,896
[ALL LAUGHING]

1310
01:20:16,899 --> 01:20:19,510
If my darling dad
had been here today,

1311
01:20:19,553 --> 01:20:22,034
he would have been speaking now.

1312
01:20:22,078 --> 01:20:23,819
And I know what
he would have said.

1313
01:20:23,862 --> 01:20:25,559
"Great dress, babe,

1314
01:20:25,603 --> 01:20:28,040
"but why in the hell are you
marrying the stiff in the skirt?"

1315
01:20:32,523 --> 01:20:35,874
And I would have given him the
same answer that I give you.

1316
01:20:36,788 --> 01:20:38,834
"Because I love him."

1317
01:20:38,877 --> 01:20:42,533
As John Lennon said, who
died the same year as my dad,

1318
01:20:42,576 --> 01:20:45,579
"Love is the answer.
And you know that for sure."

1319
01:20:47,755 --> 01:20:49,453
[PEOPLE APPLAUDING]

1320
01:20:50,933 --> 01:20:54,501
Oh, oh, and one more thing.

1321
01:20:54,545 --> 01:20:56,677
Someone had told me here,
confidentially,

1322
01:20:56,721 --> 01:20:58,917
that if things with Hamish didn't
work out, that he would step in.

1323
01:20:58,941 --> 01:21:01,508
I just wanted to say thanks,
and I'll keep you posted.

1324
01:21:07,253 --> 01:21:08,951
Bravo!

1325
01:21:08,994 --> 01:21:12,128
MAN: And now, my lords, ladies
and gentlemen, Sir Hamish Banks.

1326
01:21:19,135 --> 01:21:21,746
Anyone involved in politics
for the last 20 years

1327
01:21:21,789 --> 01:21:23,922
has gotten used to being
upstaged by a woman.

1328
01:21:23,966 --> 01:21:26,098
[PEOPLE LAUGH]

1329
01:21:26,142 --> 01:21:29,319
HAMISH: I didn't expect it to
happen to me on my wedding day.

1330
01:21:29,362 --> 01:21:32,104
However, I must also say

1331
01:21:32,148 --> 01:21:35,325
that I'm quite happy to
be upstaged by this woman

1332
01:21:35,368 --> 01:21:37,066
for the rest of my life.

1333
01:21:37,109 --> 01:21:39,068
Oh, dear, is that some
barracking at the back?

1334
01:21:39,111 --> 01:21:41,070
Again, something
we politicians are used to.

1335
01:21:42,375 --> 01:21:43,463
[STAMMERING] Find a doctor.

1336
01:21:43,507 --> 01:21:45,291
Right. Okay.

1337
01:21:45,335 --> 01:21:48,033
First of all, I want to extend my
compliments to the bridesmaids.

1338
01:21:48,077 --> 01:21:50,383
You did your duty superbly.

1339
01:21:50,427 --> 01:21:52,472
And, obviously,
I intend to use you

1340
01:21:52,516 --> 01:21:54,300
every time I get married
from now on.

1341
01:21:54,344 --> 01:21:55,823
[ALL LAUGHING]

1342
01:22:01,177 --> 01:22:05,137
HAMISH: And also, I want to thank all
those wonderful ladies of the parish

1343
01:22:05,181 --> 01:22:07,313
who did the flowers
in the church.

1344
01:22:07,357 --> 01:22:11,013
The stern old building took on
a look of flushing youth today.

1345
01:22:15,017 --> 01:22:16,409
[PEOPLE APPLAUDING]

1346
01:22:19,891 --> 01:22:23,199
I remember the first time
I laid eyes on Caroline.

1347
01:22:23,242 --> 01:22:27,638
I thought to myself, "If by
any chance she's shortsighted,

1348
01:22:29,031 --> 01:22:31,903
"I might just be happy
for the rest of my life."

1349
01:22:33,644 --> 01:22:36,212
I thought I could see
my future for the first time.

1350
01:22:36,255 --> 01:22:41,869
It was a joyful one,
for years and years to come.

1351
01:22:48,267 --> 01:22:52,010
ALL: ♪ For he's
a jolly good fellow

1352
01:22:52,054 --> 01:22:55,144
♪ For they are
jolly good fellows

1353
01:22:55,187 --> 01:23:00,062
♪ For they are
jolly good fellows

1354
01:23:00,105 --> 01:23:02,151
♪ And so say all of us

1355
01:23:22,171 --> 01:23:23,999
[ENGINE STARTS]

1356
01:24:13,135 --> 01:24:14,962
Good morning,

1357
01:24:15,006 --> 01:24:18,227
and a warm welcome to
you all on this cold day.

1358
01:24:18,270 --> 01:24:20,925
Our service will begin
in a few minutes.

1359
01:24:20,968 --> 01:24:23,928
But first we have asked Matthew,

1360
01:24:23,971 --> 01:24:26,496
Gareth's closest friend,
to say a few words.

1361
01:24:36,984 --> 01:24:40,118
Gareth used to prefer
funerals to weddings.

1362
01:24:40,162 --> 01:24:44,122
He said it was easier to get
enthusiastic about a ceremony

1363
01:24:44,166 --> 01:24:47,125
one had an outside chance of
eventually being involved in.

1364
01:24:50,172 --> 01:24:51,410
In order to prepare this speech,

1365
01:24:51,434 --> 01:24:54,089
I rang a few people
to get a general picture

1366
01:24:54,132 --> 01:24:56,961
of how Gareth was regarded
by those who met him.

1367
01:24:59,181 --> 01:25:01,313
"Fat" seems to have been a word

1368
01:25:01,357 --> 01:25:03,185
people most connected with him.

1369
01:25:05,796 --> 01:25:08,103
"Terribly rude"
also rang a lot of bells.

1370
01:25:10,540 --> 01:25:14,631
"So very fat and very rude" seems to
have been the stranger's viewpoint.

1371
01:25:16,502 --> 01:25:18,176
On the other hand, some of
you have been kind enough

1372
01:25:18,200 --> 01:25:20,593
to ring me and let me know
that you loved him,

1373
01:25:20,637 --> 01:25:24,249
which I know he would have
been thrilled to hear.

1374
01:25:24,293 --> 01:25:26,599
You remember
his fabulous hospitality.

1375
01:25:27,948 --> 01:25:30,081
His strange
experimental cooking.

1376
01:25:31,996 --> 01:25:34,781
The recipe for
duck a la banana, fortunately,

1377
01:25:34,825 --> 01:25:36,827
goes with him to his grave.

1378
01:25:38,394 --> 01:25:39,394
Most of all,

1379
01:25:40,613 --> 01:25:43,268
you tell me of his
enormous capacity for joy.

1380
01:25:43,312 --> 01:25:45,140
And when joyful...

1381
01:25:46,880 --> 01:25:49,231
When joyful,
for highly vocal drunkenness.

1382
01:25:52,234 --> 01:25:55,150
But I hope joyful is how
you will remember him.

1383
01:25:57,804 --> 01:25:59,850
Not stuck in a box in a church.

1384
01:26:03,984 --> 01:26:07,249
Pick your favorite of his waistcoats
and remember him that way.

1385
01:26:08,250 --> 01:26:11,166
The most splendid, replete,

1386
01:26:13,385 --> 01:26:14,778
big-hearted...

1387
01:26:17,389 --> 01:26:20,044
Weak-hearted, as it turned out,

1388
01:26:20,087 --> 01:26:22,177
and jolly bugger
most of us ever met.

1389
01:26:26,137 --> 01:26:29,096
As for me, you may ask
how I will remember him.

1390
01:26:31,011 --> 01:26:32,578
What I thought of him.

1391
01:26:37,279 --> 01:26:40,107
Unfortunately,
there I run out of words.

1392
01:26:43,807 --> 01:26:46,244
Perhaps you will forgive me
if I turn from my own feelings

1393
01:26:46,288 --> 01:26:48,638
to the words of
another splendid bugger,

1394
01:26:49,595 --> 01:26:51,031
W.H. Auden.

1395
01:26:52,424 --> 01:26:54,470
This is actually
what I want to say.

1396
01:26:58,300 --> 01:27:00,215
"Stop all the clocks

1397
01:27:00,258 --> 01:27:01,825
"Cut off the telephone

1398
01:27:03,305 --> 01:27:06,221
"Prevent the dog from barking
with a juicy bone

1399
01:27:08,832 --> 01:27:11,226
"Silence the pianos,
and with muffled drum

1400
01:27:12,444 --> 01:27:14,054
"bring out the coffin

1401
01:27:15,142 --> 01:27:16,709
"Let the mourners come

1402
01:27:18,450 --> 01:27:21,366
"Let the airplanes circle,
moaning overhead

1403
01:27:21,410 --> 01:27:23,194
"Scribbling on the sky
the message

1404
01:27:24,282 --> 01:27:25,805
"'He is dead'

1405
01:27:27,503 --> 01:27:31,071
"Put great bows around the
white necks of the public doves

1406
01:27:33,509 --> 01:27:36,251
"Let traffic policemen
wear black cotton gloves

1407
01:27:38,514 --> 01:27:42,257
"He was my north, my south,
my east, and west

1408
01:27:43,997 --> 01:27:46,696
"My working week
and my Sunday rest

1409
01:27:49,307 --> 01:27:52,876
"My noon, my midnight,
my talk, my song

1410
01:27:56,314 --> 01:27:58,490
"I thought that love
would last forever

1411
01:28:00,318 --> 01:28:01,885
[SOBBING] "I was wrong

1412
01:28:06,019 --> 01:28:07,891
"The stars are not wanted now

1413
01:28:09,501 --> 01:28:11,024
"Put out every one

1414
01:28:13,331 --> 01:28:15,464
"Pack up the moon
and dismantle the sun

1415
01:28:19,163 --> 01:28:21,339
"Pour away the ocean
and sweep up the wood

1416
01:28:23,776 --> 01:28:26,301
"For nothing now can
ever come to any good"

1417
01:28:47,539 --> 01:28:49,019
MAN: Bye, now.

1418
01:28:52,762 --> 01:28:54,633
I'll take you home, Scarlett.

1419
01:29:04,556 --> 01:29:06,689
It was good of you to come.

1420
01:29:06,732 --> 01:29:09,039
Must have been the shortest
honeymoon in history.

1421
01:29:09,082 --> 01:29:11,563
No, it's fine.
We'll do it some other time.

1422
01:29:16,655 --> 01:29:18,831
You know, that thing
you said in the street?

1423
01:29:18,875 --> 01:29:20,572
Yes. I'm sorry about that.

1424
01:29:20,616 --> 01:29:23,358
No, I liked it.
I liked you saying it.

1425
01:29:35,979 --> 01:29:38,416
Charlie, I'll take
Scarlett home, all right?

1426
01:29:38,460 --> 01:29:39,460
Yeah.

1427
01:29:40,244 --> 01:29:41,288
Darling Fi.

1428
01:29:50,515 --> 01:29:52,430
Walk, Charlie?

1429
01:29:52,474 --> 01:29:54,606
Yeah. Yeah,
that would be grand.

1430
01:29:58,480 --> 01:29:59,785
Never felt like that.

1431
01:29:59,829 --> 01:30:03,572
I mean, something
vaguely similar for Jilly,

1432
01:30:03,615 --> 01:30:05,443
when I was young.

1433
01:30:05,487 --> 01:30:06,487
Jilly?

1434
01:30:07,402 --> 01:30:08,402
Labrador.

1435
01:30:10,840 --> 01:30:13,451
Yes, it's odd, isn't it?

1436
01:30:13,495 --> 01:30:15,584
All these years we've been
single and proud of it,

1437
01:30:15,627 --> 01:30:17,455
and never noticed
that two of us were,

1438
01:30:17,499 --> 01:30:20,980
for all intents and purposes,
married all this time.

1439
01:30:21,024 --> 01:30:22,591
Traitors in our midst.

1440
01:30:27,509 --> 01:30:31,426
You know, in a way, I think death is
hardest for the parents, don't you?

1441
01:30:31,469 --> 01:30:33,166
I hope I die before my children.

1442
01:30:33,689 --> 01:30:35,299
Tom,

1443
01:30:35,342 --> 01:30:38,171
there's one thing
I find really...

1444
01:30:41,523 --> 01:30:42,959
Well...

1445
01:30:43,002 --> 01:30:45,483
It's your total confidence
that you will get married.

1446
01:30:45,527 --> 01:30:48,399
I mean, what if you
never find the right girl?

1447
01:30:49,531 --> 01:30:50,880
Sorry?

1448
01:30:50,923 --> 01:30:54,623
Surely, if that service
shows anything,

1449
01:30:54,666 --> 01:30:57,452
it shows that there is such
a thing as a perfect match.

1450
01:30:57,495 --> 01:31:01,107
If we can't be like
Gareth and Matthew,

1451
01:31:01,151 --> 01:31:03,588
then maybe we should
just let it go.

1452
01:31:03,632 --> 01:31:06,330
Some of us are not
going to get married.

1453
01:31:06,373 --> 01:31:08,288
Well, I don't know, Charlie.

1454
01:31:09,768 --> 01:31:12,249
The truth is, unlike you,

1455
01:31:12,292 --> 01:31:15,513
I never expected
the thunderbolt.

1456
01:31:15,557 --> 01:31:19,474
I always just hoped that I'd
meet some nice, friendly girl,

1457
01:31:19,517 --> 01:31:20,953
like the look of her.

1458
01:31:20,997 --> 01:31:24,261
Hope the look of me didn't
make her physically sick.

1459
01:31:24,304 --> 01:31:28,483
Then pop the question and
settle down and be happy.

1460
01:31:30,702 --> 01:31:32,269
It worked for my parents.

1461
01:31:32,312 --> 01:31:34,663
Well, apart from the
divorce and all that.

1462
01:31:34,706 --> 01:31:37,317
I'll give you six months
at the outside, Tom.

1463
01:31:38,710 --> 01:31:41,844
Yeah, maybe you're right.

1464
01:31:41,887 --> 01:31:45,195
Maybe all this "waiting
for one true love" stuff

1465
01:31:45,935 --> 01:31:47,414
gets you nowhere.

1466
01:31:49,895 --> 01:31:51,506
[ALARM CLOCK RINGING]

1467
01:31:58,774 --> 01:31:59,774
[ALARM CLOCKS RINGING]

1468
01:32:01,559 --> 01:32:02,560
Hmm?

1469
01:32:05,607 --> 01:32:07,260
What the fuck is going on?

1470
01:32:07,609 --> 01:32:08,784
[GRUNTING]

1471
01:32:12,352 --> 01:32:14,790
I thought we better make
absolutely sure we weren't late.

1472
01:32:16,618 --> 01:32:18,054
Excellent wedding hairstyle.

1473
01:32:18,620 --> 01:32:20,752
Charles &

1474
01:32:20,796 --> 01:32:22,362
Ten months later

1475
01:32:22,406 --> 01:32:25,540
CHARLES: Matthew, the best-looking
best man in the world.

1476
01:32:26,453 --> 01:32:27,453
Listen.

1477
01:32:29,239 --> 01:32:30,893
Thank you for doing this today.

1478
01:32:30,936 --> 01:32:32,155
Of course.

1479
01:32:35,506 --> 01:32:37,160
I wish Gareth was here.

1480
01:32:38,640 --> 01:32:40,250
Bet he does, too.

1481
01:32:43,514 --> 01:32:45,168
I'm sorry I was so late.

1482
01:32:45,211 --> 01:32:46,822
The others are just
parking the car.

1483
01:32:46,865 --> 01:32:49,259
I thought we'd all go with Tom.

1484
01:32:49,302 --> 01:32:51,261
Late? So late?

1485
01:32:51,304 --> 01:32:52,567
Yeah, it's 9:45.

1486
01:32:53,176 --> 01:32:54,569
9:45?

1487
01:32:54,612 --> 01:32:56,962
Yep, 45 minutes
till "I do."

1488
01:32:58,224 --> 01:33:00,836
Bloody Tom! I told him
to set the alarm for 8:00.

1489
01:33:01,488 --> 01:33:02,577
Fuck!

1490
01:33:07,843 --> 01:33:08,844
Scarlett.

1491
01:33:09,496 --> 01:33:10,628
Oh, hi.

1492
01:33:10,672 --> 01:33:11,977
You ready?

1493
01:33:12,021 --> 01:33:14,066
Absolutely.
Give me 20 seconds.

1494
01:33:19,245 --> 01:33:20,420
[TIRES SCREECHING]

1495
01:33:24,424 --> 01:33:25,643
Time?
Honestly?

1496
01:33:25,687 --> 01:33:27,297
Yes! Time?

1497
01:33:27,340 --> 01:33:28,298
It's about 8:50.

1498
01:33:28,341 --> 01:33:29,865
[ALL CHUCKLING]

1499
01:33:47,360 --> 01:33:48,666
Bastards.

1500
01:33:51,538 --> 01:33:54,237
WOMAN: Jessica, stop jumping
up and down, please.

1501
01:33:54,716 --> 01:33:56,282
[GIRLS GIGGLING]

1502
01:33:58,328 --> 01:34:01,244
One, two, three, smile!

1503
01:34:04,029 --> 01:34:05,727
This is splendid tuck.

1504
01:34:05,770 --> 01:34:08,294
Yes, I think I might
say a little word.

1505
01:34:08,904 --> 01:34:10,993
Well, as many of you know,

1506
01:34:11,036 --> 01:34:14,126
I have been a close observer of
Charles' love life for many years now.

1507
01:34:14,170 --> 01:34:17,260
But recently, I'd started
to despair and fear

1508
01:34:17,303 --> 01:34:19,088
that really he was
married to us lot.

1509
01:34:19,131 --> 01:34:21,656
Apart from the fact that
we won't have his babies.

1510
01:34:21,699 --> 01:34:22,961
I don't know about that.

1511
01:34:23,005 --> 01:34:24,789
Fortunately, it's all
turned out splendidly.

1512
01:34:24,833 --> 01:34:27,444
The girl in question
is, sadly, crazy,

1513
01:34:27,487 --> 01:34:29,533
but perhaps
that's why he loves her.

1514
01:34:29,576 --> 01:34:32,797
So I'd like to propose a toast to
my Charlie and his beautiful girl

1515
01:34:32,841 --> 01:34:34,538
on this tragic day.

1516
01:34:34,581 --> 01:34:37,149
So be happy and don't forget us.

1517
01:34:37,193 --> 01:34:38,324
CHARLES: Thank you.

1518
01:34:38,368 --> 01:34:40,109
To Charles and Duckface.

1519
01:34:40,152 --> 01:34:42,067
ALL: To Charles and Duckface!

1520
01:34:48,726 --> 01:34:50,859
What do you think?
You look divine.

1521
01:34:50,902 --> 01:34:52,730
It does work, doesn't it?

1522
01:34:52,774 --> 01:34:53,774
Yes.

1523
01:34:56,734 --> 01:35:00,651
I'd like to thank Fiona for those
charming words about my future wife.

1524
01:35:00,695 --> 01:35:02,760
And I'd like to take this
opportunity, before the day starts,

1525
01:35:02,784 --> 01:35:05,351
to read a little message
from her to you all.

1526
01:35:05,395 --> 01:35:07,266
This is exciting.

1527
01:35:07,310 --> 01:35:10,748
She says, "If any of you come near
the house, I'll set the dogs on you."

1528
01:35:10,792 --> 01:35:13,098
I think that's rather
a nice touch.

1529
01:35:16,101 --> 01:35:18,103
[CHUCKLING] "I'll
set the dogs on you."

1530
01:35:19,975 --> 01:35:20,975
John, hi.

1531
01:35:22,325 --> 01:35:24,370
You made it. Good.
Oh, yes.

1532
01:35:24,414 --> 01:35:25,937
I hope me damn sister turns up.

1533
01:35:25,981 --> 01:35:27,896
Not much of a wedding
without a bride.

1534
01:35:27,939 --> 01:35:28,940
Tom.

1535
01:35:29,811 --> 01:35:31,160
Charlie.
John.

1536
01:35:31,203 --> 01:35:33,423
Bit of a poor show,
you not having a stag night.

1537
01:35:33,466 --> 01:35:35,207
Oh, we did. We did.
We did. We did.

1538
01:35:35,251 --> 01:35:38,123
We didn't think it was a very good
idea in this day and age, so...

1539
01:35:38,820 --> 01:35:39,908
Really?

1540
01:35:53,399 --> 01:35:55,271
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

1541
01:36:00,842 --> 01:36:03,366
Fi, you do look lovely today.

1542
01:36:03,409 --> 01:36:06,761
Yes, as you can see, I've
abandoned my traditional black.

1543
01:36:06,804 --> 01:36:08,806
[CHUCKLES]
Yes, so you have.

1544
01:36:08,850 --> 01:36:11,461
From now on, I shall be
all the colors of the rainbow

1545
01:36:11,504 --> 01:36:14,769
and fall in love with someone
who fancies me for a change.

1546
01:36:16,074 --> 01:36:17,162
Darling Fi.

1547
01:36:24,866 --> 01:36:26,389
Oh, look.

1548
01:36:26,432 --> 01:36:28,217
What?
Lipstick everywhere.

1549
01:36:28,260 --> 01:36:30,132
That won't do at all, will it?

1550
01:36:30,175 --> 01:36:31,698
[BELLS TOLLING]

1551
01:36:33,004 --> 01:36:34,179
Hi. Hi.

1552
01:36:51,718 --> 01:36:52,807
Good luck.

1553
01:36:58,900 --> 01:37:01,598
SCARLETT: Hello.
Glad you could come.

1554
01:37:01,641 --> 01:37:02,860
MATTHEW: How are you?

1555
01:37:02,904 --> 01:37:04,949
Groom's on the right.
Bride's on the left.

1556
01:37:10,302 --> 01:37:11,869
Oh, my God!

1557
01:37:12,348 --> 01:37:13,828
[WAILING]

1558
01:37:16,439 --> 01:37:19,834
[GRUNTS] I thought you'd
gone back to Texas.

1559
01:37:19,877 --> 01:37:21,836
Without you, never.

1560
01:37:26,275 --> 01:37:27,319
Good luck.

1561
01:37:32,324 --> 01:37:33,848
Bride or groom?

1562
01:37:36,372 --> 01:37:37,721
Bride or groom?

1563
01:37:38,765 --> 01:37:41,290
It should be perfectly
obvious I'm neither.

1564
01:37:42,160 --> 01:37:43,292
Great God!

1565
01:37:44,380 --> 01:37:45,990
Bride or groom?

1566
01:37:46,034 --> 01:37:47,035
Bride.

1567
01:37:57,349 --> 01:38:00,178
Yes, fine.

1568
01:38:03,965 --> 01:38:06,489
You know, I've got a
feeling we've met before.

1569
01:38:06,532 --> 01:38:10,275
We have.
About 25 years ago.

1570
01:38:10,319 --> 01:38:13,061
I'm second cousin Harold's
daughter, Deirdre. You're Tom.

1571
01:38:13,757 --> 01:38:15,367
Good Lord!

1572
01:38:15,411 --> 01:38:17,892
So you're family.
Yes.

1573
01:38:19,023 --> 01:38:20,372
Only very distant.

1574
01:38:20,416 --> 01:38:22,897
Well, yes, of course.

1575
01:38:24,768 --> 01:38:27,945
[STUTTERING]
You said you were bride?

1576
01:38:27,989 --> 01:38:29,120
Yes.

1577
01:38:29,164 --> 01:38:30,600
Well, do sit.

1578
01:38:31,644 --> 01:38:33,908
Do sit here, Deirdre.

1579
01:38:38,651 --> 01:38:39,739
Golly.

1580
01:38:41,306 --> 01:38:42,394
Thunderbolt city.

1581
01:38:44,179 --> 01:38:45,310
BERNARD: Hello, Matthew.

1582
01:38:46,572 --> 01:38:48,009
Hello, Charles.

1583
01:38:48,052 --> 01:38:49,488
Bernard, how are you?

1584
01:38:49,532 --> 01:38:51,099
Exhausted, actually.

1585
01:38:51,142 --> 01:38:53,144
That's funny. Charles.

1586
01:39:00,238 --> 01:39:01,848
Hi.
Hi.

1587
01:39:04,112 --> 01:39:06,201
You look lovely.

1588
01:39:06,244 --> 01:39:08,943
But then, as you know, I always
did like you dressed for weddings.

1589
01:39:08,986 --> 01:39:10,074
And on time!

1590
01:39:10,118 --> 01:39:12,729
Yep! Extraordinary thing,
isn't it?

1591
01:39:12,772 --> 01:39:14,035
How's Hamish?

1592
01:39:14,078 --> 01:39:16,646
Oh, he's fine, I believe.

1593
01:39:17,473 --> 01:39:19,301
You believe?

1594
01:39:19,344 --> 01:39:21,999
Well, yes, he wasn't
the man for me after all.

1595
01:39:25,350 --> 01:39:26,743
You left him?

1596
01:39:26,786 --> 01:39:28,136
We left each other.

1597
01:39:31,226 --> 01:39:32,575
When?

1598
01:39:32,618 --> 01:39:35,230
Oh, a few months now.

1599
01:39:35,273 --> 01:39:39,364
March was hell.
By April, it was sordid.

1600
01:39:39,408 --> 01:39:42,063
That's absolutely the last time I
marry someone three times my age.

1601
01:39:42,106 --> 01:39:44,674
MATTHEW: Charlie?
Charles, time to travel.

1602
01:39:46,110 --> 01:39:47,242
Yeah. Yeah.

1603
01:39:50,071 --> 01:39:51,289
Coming. Good.

1604
01:39:51,855 --> 01:39:52,855
Good.

1605
01:39:55,598 --> 01:39:58,079
So why didn't you
get in touch, then?

1606
01:39:58,122 --> 01:40:00,037
I did think about it.

1607
01:40:00,081 --> 01:40:03,910
I wanted to,
but I was in a state.

1608
01:40:06,087 --> 01:40:09,003
So anyway,
I don't want to keep you.

1609
01:40:10,178 --> 01:40:13,007
And I'll see you afterwards.

1610
01:40:13,050 --> 01:40:14,834
Yeah. Fine, excellent.

1611
01:40:14,878 --> 01:40:15,878
Wait.

1612
01:40:21,537 --> 01:40:23,495
I'll show you to your seat.

1613
01:40:25,106 --> 01:40:27,108
Just showing her to her seat.

1614
01:40:40,121 --> 01:40:43,124
Our timing's been
really bad, hasn't it?

1615
01:40:43,167 --> 01:40:44,560
It's been bad, yes.

1616
01:40:45,474 --> 01:40:47,258
It's been a disaster.

1617
01:40:48,172 --> 01:40:49,956
It has, as you say, been

1618
01:40:51,784 --> 01:40:53,047
very bad indeed.

1619
01:40:57,355 --> 01:40:59,357
God, it's lovely to see you.

1620
01:41:02,317 --> 01:41:04,058
Well, good luck.

1621
01:41:05,146 --> 01:41:06,669
It's pretty easy.

1622
01:41:06,712 --> 01:41:09,672
Just say "I do" whenever
anyone asks you a question.

1623
01:41:15,765 --> 01:41:17,027
Um...

1624
01:41:19,334 --> 01:41:21,553
Could you just
give me a sec, Matthew?

1625
01:41:22,772 --> 01:41:25,079
Yes, of course.
Freshen up at will.

1626
01:41:44,402 --> 01:41:45,838
Dear Lord,

1627
01:41:47,188 --> 01:41:52,541
forgive me for what
I'm about to say

1628
01:41:52,584 --> 01:41:55,109
in this magnificent
place of worship.

1629
01:41:57,285 --> 01:41:58,285
Bugger!

1630
01:42:00,375 --> 01:42:01,375
Bugger!

1631
01:42:03,247 --> 01:42:06,120
Bugger! Bugger!
Bugger! Bugger!

1632
01:42:09,210 --> 01:42:10,559
Can I help at all?

1633
01:42:11,342 --> 01:42:12,169
Huh?

1634
01:42:12,213 --> 01:42:13,301
No. Thanks.

1635
01:42:14,215 --> 01:42:15,215
Sorry.

1636
01:42:17,087 --> 01:42:19,698
Vocal exercises.
Big church.

1637
01:42:19,742 --> 01:42:22,048
Excellent. Often do
the same myself.

1638
01:42:22,092 --> 01:42:24,703
Uh, not exactly the
same vocab, obviously.

1639
01:42:24,747 --> 01:42:26,183
Rather more alleluias.

1640
01:42:26,227 --> 01:42:27,315
[CHUCKLES]

1641
01:42:27,358 --> 01:42:28,577
I'll leave you.

1642
01:42:31,971 --> 01:42:33,582
[BELLS TOLLING]

1643
01:42:44,070 --> 01:42:46,116
[BABY BABBLING]

1644
01:42:47,813 --> 01:42:49,250
Bride's arriving.

1645
01:42:49,293 --> 01:42:51,817
Fabulous! We seem to
have lost the groom.

1646
01:42:52,905 --> 01:42:54,211
You see if you can stall her,

1647
01:42:54,255 --> 01:42:55,212
and I'll see if I can find him.

1648
01:42:55,256 --> 01:42:56,257
Roger. Wilco.

1649
01:43:04,569 --> 01:43:06,180
Charles.
Hmm?

1650
01:43:08,007 --> 01:43:09,444
It's good to see you.

1651
01:43:12,403 --> 01:43:14,144
Yeah. Yeah.

1652
01:43:16,842 --> 01:43:20,194
Matt, what do we think
about marriage?

1653
01:43:21,282 --> 01:43:23,066
Oh, gosh, uh...

1654
01:43:24,285 --> 01:43:27,244
Well, I think it's really good...
Hmm.

1655
01:43:27,288 --> 01:43:30,813
If you love the person
with all your heart.

1656
01:43:30,856 --> 01:43:32,467
[STAMMERING]
Well, exactly.

1657
01:43:33,294 --> 01:43:34,294
Quite.

1658
01:43:37,428 --> 01:43:41,215
All these weddings.
All these years.

1659
01:43:43,173 --> 01:43:46,437
All that blasted salmon
and champagne.

1660
01:43:46,481 --> 01:43:48,352
Here I am on my own wedding day,

1661
01:43:48,396 --> 01:43:52,313
and I'm still thinking.

1662
01:43:53,488 --> 01:43:55,098
Can I ask about what?

1663
01:43:55,664 --> 01:43:57,143
Um...

1664
01:43:58,319 --> 01:44:00,408
No.

1665
01:44:00,451 --> 01:44:01,931
No, I think best not.

1666
01:44:03,324 --> 01:44:05,239
I'm terribly sorry,
there's a bit of a delay.

1667
01:44:05,282 --> 01:44:06,477
There's a slight problem
with the flowers.

1668
01:44:06,501 --> 01:44:07,719
Flowers? What?

1669
01:44:07,763 --> 01:44:09,721
Unfortunately, there seems to be

1670
01:44:09,765 --> 01:44:12,265
a staggeringly high proportion of hay
fever sufferers on the congregation

1671
01:44:12,289 --> 01:44:14,311
and they've been stuck right
next to the damn flowers.

1672
01:44:14,335 --> 01:44:17,425
So we're just moving them.
The congregation.

1673
01:44:17,468 --> 01:44:20,055
Don't want the damn vows to be
obliterated by the sound of sneezing.

1674
01:44:20,079 --> 01:44:23,257
Charles, would it be out of place for
me to say that time is ticking by?

1675
01:44:26,608 --> 01:44:28,653
What's happening?
Tell me.

1676
01:44:33,310 --> 01:44:35,181
O God.

1677
01:44:36,008 --> 01:44:39,011
I just saw Carrie
and she's separated.

1678
01:44:40,056 --> 01:44:42,450
Charles. It's your wedding
day.

1679
01:44:44,321 --> 01:44:45,844
[WHISPERING]

1680
01:44:45,888 --> 01:44:47,672
Should've started by now.

1681
01:44:50,327 --> 01:44:52,068
I think I've fooled them so far.

1682
01:44:52,111 --> 01:44:53,741
It's a great advantage of having
a reputation for being stupid.

1683
01:44:53,765 --> 01:44:55,158
People are less
suspicious of you.

1684
01:44:55,637 --> 01:44:57,334
What's your advice?

1685
01:44:58,030 --> 01:45:00,642
You've got three choices,
one, go ahead with it.

1686
01:45:02,992 --> 01:45:05,647
Two, go outside and say,
"Sorry folks, it's all off!"

1687
01:45:06,474 --> 01:45:08,519
Not tempting. Next?

1688
01:45:09,738 --> 01:45:11,479
Third...

1689
01:45:13,655 --> 01:45:15,787
I can't think of a third.

1690
01:45:17,180 --> 01:45:18,355
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

1691
01:45:18,399 --> 01:45:19,617
Hello.

1692
01:45:21,445 --> 01:45:24,274
Here you are.
Ready to face the enemy?

1693
01:45:26,668 --> 01:45:27,756
Are we?

1694
01:45:32,369 --> 01:45:33,369
Yes.

1695
01:45:35,720 --> 01:45:37,069
Excellent.

1696
01:46:00,441 --> 01:46:02,356
[WEDDING MARCH PLAYING]

1697
01:46:32,037 --> 01:46:33,387
Not so tight, Dad!

1698
01:47:03,025 --> 01:47:04,592
Dearly beloved,

1699
01:47:04,635 --> 01:47:07,464
we are gathered together
here in the sight of God

1700
01:47:07,508 --> 01:47:10,293
and in the face
of this congregation

1701
01:47:10,336 --> 01:47:14,079
to join together this man and
this woman in holy matrimony,

1702
01:47:14,123 --> 01:47:16,430
which is an honorable estate

1703
01:47:16,473 --> 01:47:19,607
instituted of God in the time
of man's innocence.

1704
01:47:19,650 --> 01:47:22,261
Signifying unto us
the mystical union

1705
01:47:22,305 --> 01:47:25,613
that is betwixt
Christ and His church,

1706
01:47:25,656 --> 01:47:29,051
and therefore is not
by any to be enterprised,

1707
01:47:29,094 --> 01:47:32,750
nor taken in hand unadvisedly,
lightly, or wantonly,

1708
01:47:32,794 --> 01:47:37,102
but reverently, discreetly,
advisedly, soberly,

1709
01:47:37,886 --> 01:47:39,496
and in the fear of God.

1710
01:47:40,976 --> 01:47:43,500
Therefore, if any man
can show any just cause

1711
01:47:43,544 --> 01:47:46,329
why they may not lawfully
be joined together

1712
01:47:46,372 --> 01:47:50,464
let him speak now, or else
hereafter forever hold his peace.

1713
01:47:53,118 --> 01:47:54,337
[RAPPING]

1714
01:47:55,860 --> 01:47:58,515
I'm sorry, does someone
have something to say?

1715
01:48:05,740 --> 01:48:07,132
VICAR: Yes? What is it?

1716
01:48:07,176 --> 01:48:08,482
[WHISPERS]
He's David, I think.

1717
01:48:09,874 --> 01:48:11,310
One second.

1718
01:48:11,746 --> 01:48:13,269
What's going on?

1719
01:48:15,010 --> 01:48:17,142
I thought of a third option.

1720
01:48:18,753 --> 01:48:20,798
What?

1721
01:48:21,233 --> 01:48:22,278
Will you translate?

1722
01:48:22,321 --> 01:48:23,714
What's going on, Charles?

1723
01:48:23,758 --> 01:48:24,280
Charles, what?

1724
01:48:24,323 --> 01:48:26,282
Translate what?

1725
01:48:26,325 --> 01:48:30,068
He wants me to translate
what he's saying.

1726
01:48:30,112 --> 01:48:31,679
What is he saying?

1727
01:48:32,375 --> 01:48:34,682
I think the groom is
having doubts...

1728
01:48:34,725 --> 01:48:38,207
He says, "I suspect the
groom is having doubts.

1729
01:48:38,250 --> 01:48:40,383
"I suspect the groom
would like to delay."

1730
01:48:41,079 --> 01:48:42,535
I think the groom really
loves someone else.

1731
01:48:42,559 --> 01:48:43,473
"I suspect the groom...

1732
01:48:43,517 --> 01:48:44,866
That's true, isn't it, Charles?

1733
01:48:45,431 --> 01:48:46,694
"I suspect the groom..."

1734
01:48:48,260 --> 01:48:50,262
Because, Charlie, this is
for the rest of your life.

1735
01:48:51,916 --> 01:48:55,920
Finally, you must marry the person
you love with your whole heart.

1736
01:48:56,617 --> 01:48:58,880
And by the way, your flies
are undone.

1737
01:48:59,489 --> 01:49:00,795
What's he saying?

1738
01:49:04,015 --> 01:49:05,060
He says

1739
01:49:06,627 --> 01:49:08,150
he suspects the groom

1740
01:49:09,630 --> 01:49:11,196
loves someone else.

1741
01:49:11,240 --> 01:49:12,589
[PEOPLE MURMURING]

1742
01:49:12,633 --> 01:49:15,549
And do you?
Do you love someone else?

1743
01:49:16,245 --> 01:49:17,551
Do you, Charles?

1744
01:49:29,432 --> 01:49:30,259
I do.

1745
01:49:30,302 --> 01:49:31,565
[SCREAMS]

1746
01:49:34,524 --> 01:49:36,657
[YELLING]

1747
01:49:36,700 --> 01:49:39,181
Get out of my way!
Let me kill him!

1748
01:49:44,665 --> 01:49:46,405
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

1749
01:49:49,321 --> 01:49:50,321
Blimey.

1750
01:49:52,673 --> 01:49:55,371
At least it's one
we won't forget.

1751
01:49:55,414 --> 01:49:58,374
I mean, lot of weddings just
blend into each other, don't they?

1752
01:49:58,417 --> 01:49:59,854
Oh, for God's sake.

1753
01:49:59,897 --> 01:50:02,204
But this one that will really
stick out in the memory.

1754
01:50:02,247 --> 01:50:04,815
For not actually including
a wedding service.

1755
01:50:04,859 --> 01:50:06,861
FIONA: Poor girl.

1756
01:50:06,904 --> 01:50:08,384
No, I mean it, poor girl!

1757
01:50:08,427 --> 01:50:10,386
I mean, she's not my
favorite person in the world,

1758
01:50:10,429 --> 01:50:12,320
but I think that may have been an
unforgivable thing that you did today.

1759
01:50:12,344 --> 01:50:14,259
I can't bear to think about it.

1760
01:50:15,652 --> 01:50:17,306
Poor Hen.

1761
01:50:17,349 --> 01:50:19,438
TOM: Though,
let's face facts.

1762
01:50:19,482 --> 01:50:24,661
I mean, if you weren't sure you
wanted to marry her today of all days,

1763
01:50:24,705 --> 01:50:26,620
i.e., your wedding day,

1764
01:50:28,491 --> 01:50:31,102
then it must be the right
decision, mustn't it?

1765
01:50:32,713 --> 01:50:34,497
Quite right, Tom.

1766
01:50:34,540 --> 01:50:37,108
It was a lovely dress. I'm sure
she'll find it useful for parties.

1767
01:50:41,286 --> 01:50:43,419
What did he say, Charles?

1768
01:50:43,462 --> 01:50:45,029
Says he blames himself.

1769
01:50:45,073 --> 01:50:48,250
TOM: Oh, absolutely not.
MATTHEW: No, you mustn't, David.

1770
01:50:49,512 --> 01:50:50,339
They all blame you too.

1771
01:50:50,382 --> 01:50:52,123
[DOORBELL RINGS]

1772
01:50:52,167 --> 01:50:56,084
No, no, no. If there's music to
be faced, I should be facing it.

1773
01:51:06,355 --> 01:51:08,705
Hello.

1774
01:51:08,749 --> 01:51:11,708
Hi! You're soaking. Come in. No, no.
I'm fine. I'm fine.

1775
01:51:11,752 --> 01:51:13,817
Comes a point when you're so
wet you can't get any wetter.

1776
01:51:13,841 --> 01:51:17,148
Okay, I'll come out.
No, please don't.

1777
01:51:17,192 --> 01:51:19,890
I just wanted
to check you're okay.

1778
01:51:19,934 --> 01:51:23,111
Not busy killing yourself
or anything, but...

1779
01:51:24,765 --> 01:51:26,418
But you're fine, so...

1780
01:51:29,378 --> 01:51:32,686
I shouldn't have come to the
church this morning. I'm sorry.

1781
01:51:33,643 --> 01:51:34,688
No! No!

1782
01:51:36,211 --> 01:51:38,387
Wait. It was all my fault.

1783
01:51:38,430 --> 01:51:39,170
I mean, I...

1784
01:51:39,214 --> 01:51:42,130
I'm the bastard here.

1785
01:51:42,173 --> 01:51:45,742
